YOLO based AI detector for localizing Roger Federer, tennis racket and tennis ball in images¶

Author: Aditya Patel¶

Goal: I built an AI system which takes in an image and detects and localizes Roger Federer, tennis racket and ball (3 classes )in it and ignores all other objects in image

MLOps Tools used: I manually albeit laboriously hand annotated labels myself for each image usingRoboflow
Algorithms - Yolov5s weights
Why Yolo5: I chose YOLO5 primarily because the algorithm automatically chooses anchor boxes to adjust to the labels. This is beyond amazing. This functionality is not available in Yolo2,Yolo3 & Yolo4 which makes customized anchor boxes a pain in the neck. Note that anchor boxes are, by default, geared towards detecting COCO objects because YOLO5 was trained on COCO. This makes hard to make customized anchor boxes of various sizes, shapes for racket, ball and Federer. Yolov5 eliminates that problem, so I used 5th version. Also Yolo5 is written in Python, not C++ and is built on top of Pytorch

Dataset: 48 images downloaded via google search.
Annotations: Manually hand annotated labels myself in Roboflow. Roboflow converted it into Yolov5 Pytorch format.

TLDR:What I found
Model performs very well overall with just 33 training images (Mean Average Precision at IOU of 0.5 is 60%). More granularly, it performs very well on racket class and ball class but not so well for Roger federer class which pulls down overall score, else it would have been even higher. This is also evident in difference in mean average precision scores for 3 classes. Racket class and ball class have high mAP score whereas Roger class does not. This is because of 2 reasons:
(1) Class imbalance. See below. Roger class is underrepresented compared to other two classes.
(2) Small number of images: I used just 17 images of Federer downloaded from google search and augmented them. With 17 more images, model would perform much better. Put this in perspective, I would need to meet someone 5-10 times to remember their face with certainty. (3) Choice of Yolov5s. I could have chosen Yolov5m or Yolov5l or yolov5x (4) My input images were tiny - 279 x 182 pixels. In today's world, no image is that small. Yolov5 was trained on 640 by 640 sized images. I could spend more time downloading larger images

The fact that my model did so well inspite of tiny images making object detection hard(just like human eye finds it hard to detect objects if image is tiny, same intuition applies for my AI model), inspite of just 17 images (real world datasets are trained on atleast 250 images of each type), indicates that there is lot of room for improvement. I am confident I can better this performance
